Date: 11 Aug 2000
From: Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@btinternet.com>
Sources: MAFF and Pig Industry

Following the 3 confirmed Classical Swine Fever (CSF) outbreaks in the UK's
largest outdoor pig breeding company, MAFF has now decided to slaughter all
pigs on the company's 6 other nursery pig rearing farms and to restrict and
test the company's 6 finishing pig farms. The farms are scattered over 3
counties of the United Kingdom.
The company whose farms are infected is one of the pioneers of multi-site
swine production systems in the UK, which are designed to reduce
transmission of enzootic diseases by early weaning of pigs from the
breeding farm to a series of remote locations. Disease transmission from
older finishing pigs to young growing pigs (weaners) is avoided by having a
series of separate finishing farms. This approach was developed by Dr. Tom
Alexander of Cambridge University and Prof. Hank Harris of Iowa State
University (see <http://www.pighealth.com/multi-site.htm>) and has become
very popular in the last few years.
The drawback, however, of having so many interconnected farms is being seen
in this outbreak of a serious exotic disease.
Further details and updates of the UK swine fever situation are located at:
<http://www.pighealth.com/csf.htm>
--
Dr. Michael Meredith, Managing Director
Pig Disease Information Centre
<http://www.pighealth.com>
<pdic@btinternet.com>
