[3
Date: 12 Aug 2000 02:00:46 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: The Journal, 11 Aug 2000 [edited

The swine holdings, one in Norfolk, and one in Essex, will now have to
slaughter all 2 850 of their pigs. A farm in Suffolk had to slaughter all 3
500 of its pigs after becoming the first in the UK to be hit by the disease
for 14 years.
The affected holding in Norfolk is a breeding farm, and supplied pigs to
the farms in Essex and Suffolk. The Essex farm was near Colchester, while
the one in Norfolk was in the Thetford area.
A ministry spokesman said the pigs would be tested during the day to
determine which ones had the disease for valuation purposes. Slaughtering
the animals was expected to begin tomorrow.
Under European Union regulations, all pigs on infected farms must be
slaughtered and their carcases destroyed. Compensation is paid at 50
percent of the market value for infected animals and 100 percent of market
value for non-infected animals.
